Knostic Home Assignment
Goal
Build a small full-stack app where you make the key design decisions. We care more about your
choices and reasoning than about specific frameworks or patterns.
The Problem
Tiny Inventory — Build a small inventory management system that tracks stores and the
products they carry. Each store can have multiple products, and each product includes basic
details such as name, category, price, and quantity in stock. The system should allow managing
stores and products, viewing products per store or across all stores, and filtering or paginating
product lists (for example, by category, price range, or stock level).
Minimal Requirements
Backend
● TypeScript HTTP server exposing a REST API with at least two related resources (e.g.,
Store ↔ Product).
● Include at least one non-trivial operation (something beyond CRUD — e.g., aggregation
or computed data).
● Include filtering and pagination on one list endpoint.
● Any persistence is acceptable (in-memory, file, SQLite, Postgres, etc.).
Frontend
● React (TypeScript) app with at least two screens (list view + detail/edit view).
● Handle loading and error states gracefully.
● Provide seed data so reviewers can interact immediately.
● Include basic input validation and clear error responses.
Infrastructure
● Dockerize everything so it runs with a single command (e.g., docker compose up
--build).
What We’ll Look For
● Clarity of choices and explanations.
● Address all aspects of making this application production-ready.
● API semantics (routes, validation, pagination, error design).
● Data modeling and querying.
● UX basics (list/detail flow, loading/error/empty states).
● Dev experience (simple Docker startup, clear project structure).
• Testing quality and rationale
• README clarity (decisions and trade-offs explained)

